{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cab3a74e-07cd-450b-a6a1-dc7092593f41","content":"## What Changed\n\nC# 14 added **implicit span conversions** (`T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>`). This causes overload resolution to now prefer:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)\n```\n\nover the old:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains(this IEnumerable<T>, T)\n```\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** and cannot be represented in expression trees. The expression tree gets built referencing the span-based method, and the interpreter fails when it tries to invoke it.\n\n## Fix\n\nDisambiguate by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`, forcing resolution back to `Enumerable.Contains`:\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nOr call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth approaches bypass the new span-preferring resolution and keep the expression tree valid.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3e6b297e-0a92-435d-84a6-4bda2f95389e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays. Let me think about what changed.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension methods. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (previously called \"extension everything\" or \"roles\"), but more relevantly, there's a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The issue is likely related to the fact that in .NET 10, `System.Array` or arrays now implement `IEnumerable<T>` more directly, or there's a new extension member resolution change.\n\n\nI'm realizing the real breaking change probably involves how `MemoryExtensions.Contains` for `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is now being prioritized in overload resolution. In .NET 9+, this method became more prominent, and with C# 14's improved extension method handling, calling `.Contains()` on an array might now resolve to the span-based version instead of the traditional `Enumerable.Contains`, which could cause issues in expression trees that don't support span types. iles it to call `MemoryExtensions.Contains` which fails at runtime when the expression tree interpreter tries to invoke it, or the expression tree captures the wrong method entirely.\n\nLet me reconsider what's actually happening here. The user says the code compiles but throws at runtime, so the expression tree is being created with a lambda that calls `.Contains()`. In C# 14, the compiler's overload resolution might now prefer `MemoryExtensions.Contains` for certain types, but I need to think through what specifically changed for arrays and whether it's related to the new `params ReadOnlySpan<T>` overloads and how extension method resolution shifted.\n\nThe real issue is that C# 14 updated extension method resolution to prefer `MemoryExtensions.Contains(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains(this IEnumerable<T>, T)` for arrays, since arrays implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` and this conversion is now considered better in overload resolution. But `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct, and expression trees can't contain ref structs, so the expression tree would fail at runtime when it tries to compile the method call.\n\nWhen writing an expression like `array.Contains(num)`, the compiler needs to resolve which overload to use, and that's where the breaking change comes in. actual .NET 10 breaking change is. In .NET 10 preview, `.Contains()` on strings and arrays now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead of `Enumerable.Contains` due to how the compiler prioritizes span-based overloads. For expression trees, the compiler might fall back to the `Enumerable` version since spans can't be represented in expression trees, or it could error at compile time—but the user says it throws at runtime with `preferInterpretation: true`, so maybe the interpreter is trying to execute a span-based method it can't handle. I'm considering whether the expression tree is being constructed dynamically through `Expression.Call` rather than via lambda conversion, which would allow the compiler to accept it but then fail at runtime when trying to invoke a method with a ref struct parameter through reflection. C# 14 introduced implicit conversions from arrays to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which changes method overload resolution so that `Contains` now prefers the `MemoryExtensions` span-based version. This breaks expression trees since they can't represent ref struct types or invoke span methods, so the solution would involve explicitly...\n\nWriting code examples...\n\nThe real question is whether this manifests as a compile-time or runtime error - it could depend on how the expression tree gets constructed and whether the compiler's overload resolution differs from what the runtime actually executes. The expression tree API doesn't validate methods at construction time, so it would accept `MemoryExtensions.Contains` even though it uses `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. The failure happens at runtime when the interpreter tries to invoke the method through reflection, since you can't pass span types through reflection—the compiled mode might handle it differently though.\n\nI keep second-guessing myself on whether the C# compiler would even allow building an expression tree with ref struct parameters in the first place, but the most likely explanation is that C# 14's implicit span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains`, and the expression tree compiles successfully but fails at runtime during interpretation.\n\nThe fix is straightforward—either cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the LINQ method, or call `Enumerable.Contains` directly. Either approach sidesteps the span issue entirely.","outputTokens":3405,"requestId":"D408:15CAA:21E3057:24CE84B:69FBB29E"},"id":"c5ff2e23-9ec5-4a5f-b63d-14f7d35b6e36","timestamp":"2026-05-06T21:30:10.647Z","parentId":"c588343c-7302-46a3-8e69-496addc144c1"}
